### Understanding Basic Code

```python
# main.py
from fastapi import FastAPI

app = FastAPI() # app  Convention     !

@app.get("/") # Decorator = Magic Function Apply -> root()

# @instanceName.httpMethod/method("Path")  

def root(): # root = login, get_user   !
    return {
    "message": "Hello World" # Dict  API = JSON!
} 
```

### Path Operation Function Order 

```python
from fastapi import FastAPI

app = FastAPI()

#   get("/"), 1st Times  Occur    !!  

@app.get("/info") # get("/") -> No
def info():
    return{
	    "name":"Mahtabul Shourav",
	    "country":"Bangladesh"
    }
    
@app.get("/")
def root(): 
    return {"msg2": "This is msg 2!"} # Order1 get("/") -> Yes

@app.get("/")
def root():
    return {"msg1": "This is msg 1!"} # Order2 get("/") -> No 
```

### HTTP GET vs POST Request

`Path Operation For GET and POST`

```python
from fastapi import FastAPI

app = FastAPI()


@app.get("/")
def root(): 
    return {"msg": "Welcome to the wolrd of backend!"} 
 

@app.get("/users") 
def user_info():
    return{
	    "name":"Mahtabul Shourav",
	    "email":"mahtabulsourav@gmail.com"
    }

@app.post("/creatposts")
def create_post():
    return {
        "msg": "Succesfully Created Post!"
    }
```

`HTTP POST Request`

![POST.PNG](data:image/png;base64,)

  POST Send / ENDPOINT HIT   Send   Data  Store
     !  Data Store   -  

```python
from fastapi.params import Body # VSCode Automatically Import This!

@app.post("/creatposts")
def create_post(payLoad: dict = Body(...)): 
# Choose Body:Params Hit Enter FastAPI Automatically Import It!!
    print(payLoad) # payLoad or Anyname You Like!
    return {
        "msg": "Succesfully Created Post!"
    }

# Body(...) It's Going To Extract All Of The Fields From The Body! Also 
# Convert Into Python Dictionary & Store It Inside payLoad Variable!
```

```bash
{'title': 'Learning API Development', 'content': 'FastAPI - Python framework for making API easily!'}
```

`Previewing On Requestly or Postman` 

```python
@app.post("/creatposts")
def create_post(payLoad: dict = Body(...)): 
    return {
        "new_post": f"Title: {payLoad['title']}, Content: {payLoad['content']}"
    }
```

`Why We Need Schema ?`
-  Body Use  Data   Pain!
- Client Side     Data Send   
- Data Valid   Check  
-  Client Side  Force  Data Send  Schema Way    
### Schema Validation with Pydantic

https://docs.pydantic.dev/latest/concepts/models/ 

```python
from fastapi import FastAPI
from fastapi.params import Body

# Pydantic  BaseModel Import  !
from pydantic import BaseModel 

app = FastAPI()



#  class Define   Name Anything! 
# Post Class Extend  BaseModel   
#  Field   Type Define  
class Post(BaseModel):
    title: str
    content: str



@app.get("/")
def root(): 
    return {"msg": "Welcome To The Wolrd Of Backend!"} 


@app.post("/creatposts")
# Pydantic Model 'Post'  Reference  Pass   
# Save 'Post' As Any VariableName
def create_post(new_post:Post): 
    #  'Post' Pydantic Model Path Operation Use 
    #   FastAPI Automatically Validate  
    #  Data  Client Side  ,  Type    
    # Error Throw  ! 
    print(new_post) # Printing Full Post!
    print(new_post.title) # Can Access Each Property!
    return {
        "data" : "new_post"
    }
```

`Body   Code Send   Preview -` 

```json
{
 "title": "Learning API Development",
 "content": "FastAPI - Python framework for making API easily!"
}
```

Pydantic Use   Data Extracting Automatic  Data / Schema Validation 
  ! 

```bash
title='Learning API Development' content='FastAPI - Python framework for making API easily!'
Learning API Development
```

`Status Code: 200OK`

Schema Validation Check -

```json
{
 "content": "FastAPI - Python framework for making API easily!"
}
```

`Adding Default Values For Fields If User Don't Provide` 

```python
class Post(BaseModel):
    title: str
    content: str
    published: bool = True

# Just Extra "published" : false/true  False/True ! 
#   By Default True  

	print(new_post.published) # For Preview!
```

`Adding Optional Field With None If User Don't Provide`

```python
from typing import Optional
class Post(BaseModel):
    title: str
    content: str
    published: bool = True
    rating: Optional[int] = None # VSCode Automatic Import So Hit Optional!

# Just Extra "published" : false/true  False/True ! 
#   By Default True  

	print(new_post.published) # For Preview!
```

`Converting Pydantic Model To Python Dictionary, Send Back To Client`

```python
def create_post(new_post:Post): 
    print(new_post.dict()) # Printing Full Post!
    return {
        "data" : new_post
    }
```
